In [[mathematics]],  '''dianalytic manifolds''' are possibly [[non-orientable]] generalizations of [[complex analytic manifold]]s. A dianalytic structure on a manifold is given by an [[atlas (topology)|atlas]] of 
[[atlas (topology)#Charts|charts]] such that the [[atlas (topology)#Transition maps|transition maps]] are either [[complex analytic map]]s or [[complex conjugate]]s of complex analytic maps.  Every dianalytic manifold is given by the [[Quotient space (topology)|quotient]] of an analytic manifold (possibly non-connected) by a fixed-point-free [[involution (mathematics)|involution]] changing the complex structure to its complex conjugate structure. Dianalytic manifolds were introduced by {{harvs|txt|last=Klein|authorlink=Felix Klein|year=1882}}, and dianalytic manifolds of 1 complex dimension are sometimes called [[Klein surface]]s.

