'''James Mills Peirce''' (May 1, 1834<ref name= case /> – March 21, 1906<ref name= cult>{{cite journal| first= Hubert| last= Kennedy| work= [[Historia Mathematica]]| title= James Mills Peirce and the Cult of Quaternions| place= | publisher= | year= 1979| volume= 6| pages= 423–429| via= [http://hubertkennedy.angelfire.com/Peirce.pdf ''Six Articles on James Mills Peirce''] (2003)| format= PDF}}</ref>) was an [[Americans|American]] mathematician and educator.<ref name= case>{{cite journal| first= Hubert| last= Kennedy| title= The Case for James Mills Peirce| work= [[Journal of Homosexuality]] | volume= 4| number= 2| date= Winter 1978| pages= 179–184| format= PDF| via= [http://hubertkennedy.angelfire.com/Peirce.pdf ''Six Articles on James Mills Peirce''] (2003)}}</ref> He taught at [[Harvard University]] for almost 50 years.<ref name= towards>{{cite journal| first= Hubert| last= Kennedy| work= [[Historia Mathematica]]| title= Towards a Biography of James Mills Peirce| place= | publisher= | year= 1979| volume= 6| pages= 195–201| via= [http://hubertkennedy.angelfire.com/Peirce.pdf ''Six Articles on James Mills Peirce''] (2003)| format= PDF}}</ref>
==Early life and family== He was the eldest son of Sarah Hunt (Mills)<ref name= towards /> Pierce and [[Benjamin Peirce]] (1809–1880), a professor of astronomy and mathematics at [[Harvard University]].<ref name= case /> The family was considered part of the [[Boston Brahmin]] elite class. The surname is pronounced to rhyme with "{{audio|en-us-purse.ogg|purse}}".<ref>{{cite web| url= http://www.iupui.edu/~peirce/news/1_3/13_4x.htm#pronunciation | title= Note on the Pronunciation of 'Peirce'| work= Peirce Project Newsletter| volume= 1| number= 3/4| date= December 1994| via= iupui.edu}}</ref> Benjamin Peirce's father, also named Benjamin, was librarian at Harvard.<ref name= reputations>{{cite news| first= Hubert| last= Kennedy| work= [[Harvard Magazine]]| title= Reputations reconsidered | publisher= | date= November–December 1982| volume= 85| number= 2| pages= 62–64| via= [http://hubertkennedy.angelfire.com/Peirce.pdf ''Six Articles on James Mills Peirce''] (2003)| format= PDF}}</ref> James had four younger siblings; one brother was philosopher, logician and professor [[Charles Sanders Peirce]] (1839–1914).<ref name= towards /> Another brother was Herbert Henry Davis Peirce (1849–1916) who was the First Secretary of the American Embassy in [[Saint Petersburg]], [[Russia]], at the end of the 19th century.<ref name= cult />
J. M. Peirce graduated from [[Harvard College]] in 1853.<ref name= case /> While an undergraduate at Harvard, he was a member of the [[Hasty Pudding Club]].<ref name= case /> He attended Harvard's law school for one year.<ref name= towards /> In 1857, he enrolled at the university's Divinity School and graduated in 1859.<ref name= towards />
==Career== Like his father, James Mills Peirce became a professor of mathematics and astronomy at Harvard.<ref name= case /><ref name= out>{{cite web| url= http://outhistory.org/exhibits/show/aspectsofqueerexistence/aspectsofqueerexistencejamesmi| title= James Mills Peirce: 'Professor X'| website= outhistory.org| publisher= Digital Humanities Initiative, [[The New School]]| date= | access-date= October 17, 2017}}</ref> He was first a Tutor in Mathematics, then a proctor at Harvard.<ref name= towards /> He was a preacher in Boston and Charleston, South Carolina, but eventually returned to academia, first as Assistant Professor of Mathematics in 1861.<ref name= towards /> He was promoted to University Professor of Mathematics in 1869, then to Perkins Professor of Astronomy and Mathematics — the same position his father once held — in 1885. He was head of the Graduate Department at Harvard from 1872 to 1895 (becoming its dean when it was converted to the Graduate School). He was the Dean of the Faculty of Arts and Sciences from 1895 to 1898.<ref name= towards />
Among his publications are ''Mathematical Tables Chiefly to Four Figures'' (1896)<ref name= out /> and ''A [[textbook|Text-Book]] of [[analytic geometry|Analytic Geometry]]; On the Basis of Professor Peirce’s Treatise'' (1857).<ref name= case /> He was considered a world authority on [[quaternions]].
